net.asrex.skillful.effect

Class Effect

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.asrex.skillful.effect.Effect
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    Ability, GlideEffect, PotionEffect, SpeedEffect

    public abstract class Effect
extends java.lang.Object
    An Effect is an optionally persistent modifier associated with a player. Effects apply to both client- and server-side code and may modify functionality that exists in either context. Effects can be uniquely identified based on their perkName and effectName, and multiple instances of the same effect could potentially be active on the same player (with different parameters).

    Effects are generally created by some EffectDefinition after a player gains or activates a perk. After creation, the perkName, effectName, definitionClass, and player properties should be set by whatever caller originally requested the EffectDefintion to construct the Effect. Finally, doEnable() should be called to begin applying the effect to the player of interest.

    Instantiated Effect objects may subscribe to the Forge event bus to handle any needed events from within their doEnable() method. If so, they should also make sure to unregister themselves when doDisable() is called.

    Note that this class will be instantiated automatically when read from player NBT. As such, subclasses must make a no-args constructor available, and implement readNBT(NBTTagCompound) and writeNBT(NBTTagCompound) to ensure proper serialization. EffectDefinition instances may pass properties to Effects in additional constructors, but Effects must maintain consistent functionality when instantiated via the no-args constructor and a subsequent readNBT(NBTTagCompound) call. Other properties, such as perkName, effectName, definitionClass, and player are also guaranteed to be set before doEnable() is executed.

        public void toggle(boolean state)
        Toggles the current effect, ensuring that the resulting state is state. If the current state as returned by #isEnabled() is already state, nothing will happen.. That is, if toggle(true) is called, either the effect is currently disabled and will be enabled, or nothing will happen.
        Parameters:
        state - the new state to ensure

      • toggle

        public void toggle()
        Toggles the current effect. If the effect is currently enabled, it will be disabled; if currently disabled, it will be enabled. The new state as returned by #isEnabled() will be reflected.

      • readNBT

        public void readNBT(net.minecraft.nbt.NBTTagCompound tag)
        Reads this effect from NBT. Subclasses may wish to store saved player data (such as a duration) that persists and updates as long as the effect remains active.

        To ensure proper deserialization, subclasses must call super.readNBT() to save additional effect metadata.

        Parameters:
        tag - the tag to read data from

      • fromNBT

        public static Effect fromNBT(net.minecraft.nbt.NBTTagCompound tag)
        Deserializes an Effect from the given NBT tag. An Effect instance of the appropriate type will be returned. Note that the player field of the returned effect must be set before executing enable().
        Parameters:
        tag - the tag to read from
        Returns:
        a deserialized Effect, or null if an error occurred and was logged
